Markerless motion capture could expand quantitative movement measurement beyond specialized laboratories, but researchers need methods that adapt to different questions, environments, and computer-vision tools. We present FreeMoCap, a free, open-source method for reconstructing 3D human movement from synchronized consumer-grade cameras. FreeMoCap pairs low-cost multi-camera recording with a modular architecture that decouples pose estimation from reconstruction and biomechanical analysis, turning pose-estimation models into interchangeable components of a shared measurement framework. We validated a six-camera FreeMoCap system against a marker-based reference during treadmill gait and clinical standing balance. The system produced biomechanically meaningful data from low-cost hardware, with gait joint-center errors generally below 30 mm, sagittal joint-angle errors of 2–5°, and center-of-mass balance metrics that showed excellent agreement with reference data. Critically, the shared framework revealed task, speed, and backend-dependent differences in markerless performance, establishing FreeMoCap as both an accessible measurement method and an extensible framework for evaluating evolving pose-estimation algorithms.


Markerless motion capture is a series of hardware and software methods to reconstruct 3D movement without the need for markers. Current solutions tend to treat each step in this pipeline as a fixed assumption, which imposes limitations on the hardware and research applications. Here, we present FreeMoCap, a free, open-source method for reconstructing 3D human movement using multiple pose-estimation algorithms with synchronization methods from multiple kinds of cameras. We validated a six-camera FreeMoCap system using low-cost webcams (\$20) against a marker-based reference during treadmill gait and clinical standing balance using three different pose estimation backends. Results showed that the system was capable of producing biomechanically meaningful data (saggital joint RMSE < 5° and [something about COM results]) and that system performance was influenced by task and pose estimation backend. These results establish that markerless motion capture is not a one-size-fits-all solution and that an extensible framework can provide a platform for evaluating and improving pose estimation algorithms for movement science applications, while making motion capture more accessible to researchers without access to specialized hardware.

