Markerless motion capture reconstructs three-dimensional movement from video without physical markers, but current implementations typically lock users into fixed hardware, a single pose estimation model, and rigid processing pipelines — limiting both the research questions that can be asked and who can ask them. Here, we present FreeMoCap, a free, open-source method that provides a complete, modular pipeline from synchronized video acquisition through biomechanical analysis, supporting interchangeable pose estimation backends and consumer-grade cameras. We validated a six-camera FreeMoCap system (~$20 webcams) against a marker-based reference (Qualisys) during treadmill gait and clinical standing balance, comparing three pose estimation backends. Sagittal joint angle errors were below 5°, spatiotemporal gait parameters showed excellent agreement (ICC > 0.90), and center-of-mass balance metrics were sensitive to condition changes — with performance varying across backends and tasks. By providing validated, open-source benchmarking infrastructure on accessible hardware, FreeMoCap lowers the barrier for researchers to collect motion capture data, evaluate pose estimation algorithms, and build a shared evidence base for markerless motion analysis.

