Dear Editors,

We wish to inquire whether the following work would be appropriate for Nature Methods.
We have developed a free, open-source markerless motion capture system that provides a full pipeline from video recording through 3D reconstruction and biomechanical analysis, runs on consumer-grade webcams, and supports interchangeable pose estimation backends. Since its release, the software (FreeMoCap)has been adopted by over 12,500 users across approximately 140 countries, used in published research spanning gait biomechanics, clinical balance, reaching kinematics, and computational linguistics, and has an active open-source community (~7,500 GitHub stars, ~3,700 Discord members).

We have completed a validation study comparing FreeMoCap against a marker-based Qualisys system across treadmill gait at five walking speeds and clinical standing balance (CTSIB-M), evaluating three pose estimation backends through the shared pipeline. A key finding is that backend choice interacts with the measurement task in ways that would not be apparent from single-domain validation — which we believe speaks to a broader methodological need in the field for open, multi-context evaluation infrastructure as markerless tools move toward clinical and research adoption.

We see this as a potential fit for Nature Methods because the contribution is primarily methodological and infrastructure-oriented: not just a validation of one system, but a framework that enables the movement science community to systematically evaluate and translate pose estimation algorithms as they continue to emerge from the computer vision field. 
